{
  "answer": "**The speaker in \"The Ruin\" contemplates the most thoroughly past ruin.**[^1]\n\nAll three poems feature speakers amid physical remnants of lost glory, but the timescale differs sharply. In \"The Wanderer,\" the earth-stepper (lone-dweller) mourns recent personal losses—his lord's death and ensuing exile—while daily \"at each dawn\" lamenting sorrows, blending lived trauma with glimpses of decayed halls.[^2] Iqbal's voice in \"Saqaliya\" is present and visceral: he weeps before Sicily's ruins \"in sight,\" invoking their \"story... concealed within your ruins\" and recent cultural memory (Muslim Sicily's fall centuries prior, but evoked as a living grave).[^3]\n\n\"The Ruin\"'s speaker, however, surveys remnants so ancient they are \"the work of giants,\" endured through \"reign after reign\" and \"a hundred generations of people,\" with walls \"by age undermined\" and cities reduced to \"wasted foundations\" long before any human memory.[^4] No personal exile or fresh grief intrudes; the ruin is mythic-prehistoric (Roman-British origins in Anglo-Saxon eyes), fully ossified into \"storm-battered dwellings\" and \"mounds,\" signaling utter remoteness from the observing moment.\n\n[^1]: *Old English Elegies*, [Chapter 16](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/16-wraetlic-is-thes-wealstan-wyrde-yebraecon-burgsted/translation/).\n\n[^2]: *Old English Elegies*, [Chapter 11](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-9462cc).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, [Chapter 21](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/21-saqaliya/translation/#p-08760e).\n\n[^4]: *Old English Elegies*, [Chapter 16](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/16-wraetlic-is-thes-wealstan-wyrde-yebraecon-burgsted/translation/#p-d0d2bd), [Chapter 16](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/16-wraetlic-is-thes-wealstan-wyrde-yebraecon-burgsted/translation/#p-ba51da).",
